<doc id="9692" url="https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=9692" title="Victory Day 60th anniversary commemorated in Russia">
<h1>Victory Day 60th anniversary commemorated in Russia</h1>
&lt;strong class="published"&gt;&lt;span id="publishDate" class="value-title" title=""&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span class="Z3988" style="display:none" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:User%3ADendodge&amp;rft_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:&amp;rft.atitle=Victory%20Day%2060th%20anniversary%20commemorated%20in%20Russia&amp;rft.jtitle=Wikinews&amp;rft.date=&amp;rft.aucorp=Wikinews+contributors&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.rights=CC-BY+2.5&amp;rft.identifier=&amp;rft.artnum="&gt; &lt;/span&gt; 

Today the 60th anniversary of &lt;a href="w%3AVictory%20Day"&gt;Victory Day&lt;/a&gt; was commemorated in &lt;a href="w%3ARussia"&gt;Russia&lt;/a&gt;, and other successor states of the &lt;a href="w%3ASoviet%20Union"&gt;Soviet Union&lt;/a&gt;.

The parade on &lt;a href="w%3ARed%20Square"&gt;Red Square&lt;/a&gt; started at 7:00 UTC. The leaders of more than 50 countries and heads of several international organisations attended the parade. &lt;a href="w%3AGeorge%20W.%20Bush"&gt;George W. Bush&lt;/a&gt; watched the parade with Russian President &lt;a href="w%3AVladimir%20Putin"&gt;Vladimir Putin&lt;/a&gt;.

Others attending included:
<ul>
BULLET::::- &lt;a href="Hu%20Jintao"&gt;Hu Jintao&lt;/a&gt; - General Secretary of the Communist Party of China
BULLET::::- &lt;a href="w%3AKofi%20Annan"&gt;Kofi Annan&lt;/a&gt; - Secretary General of the United Nations
BULLET::::- &lt;a href="w%3AJunichiro%20Koizumi"&gt;Junichiro Koizumi&lt;/a&gt; - Prime Minister of Japan
BULLET::::- &lt;a href="w%3AGerhard%20Schr%C3%B6der"&gt;Gerhard Schröder&lt;/a&gt; - Chancellor of Germany
BULLET::::- &lt;a href="%3Aw%3AJacques%20Chirac"&gt;Jacques Chirac&lt;/a&gt; - President of the French Republic

</ul>
More than 4,000 &lt;a href="w%3AWorld%20War%20II"&gt;World War II&lt;/a&gt; veterans and 7,000 military personnel were involved in the parade. The culmination was the flight of 12 planes (made up of &lt;a href="w%3ASU-25"&gt;SU-25&lt;/a&gt;s and &lt;a href="w%3AMIG-29"&gt;MIG-29&lt;/a&gt;s), which emitted white, blue and red smoke to paint a Russian flag in the air.

Average Moscow citizens were not allowed to the parade. The exits from several metropolitan stations were closed. Mass celebrations are planned to be held at &lt;a href="w%3APoklonnaya%20Gora"&gt;Poklonnaya Gora&lt;/a&gt;, Moscow's primary WW2 memorial.

Several new monuments were opened today, such as the 8-meter statue of &lt;a href="%3Aw%3ACharles%20de%20Gaulle"&gt;Charles de Gaulle&lt;/a&gt; by &lt;a href="%3Aw%3AZurab%20Tsereteli"&gt;Zurab Tsereteli&lt;/a&gt; and the monument to soldiers from Allied countries.

In the evening there was a large fireworks display.

The 60th anniversary of &lt;a href="w%3AVictory%20in%20Europe%20Day"&gt;Victory in Europe (VE) Day&lt;/a&gt; was commemorated across Europe yesterday.

