<doc id="9921" url="https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=9921" title="Irish inflation back on the rise">
<h1>Irish inflation back on the rise</h1>
&lt;strong class="published"&gt;&lt;span id="publishDate" class="value-title" title=""&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span class="Z3988" style="display:none" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:User%3ADendodge&amp;rft_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:&amp;rft.atitle=Irish%20inflation%20back%20on%20the%20rise&amp;rft.jtitle=Wikinews&amp;rft.date=&amp;rft.aucorp=Wikinews+contributors&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.rights=CC-BY+2.5&amp;rft.identifier=&amp;rft.artnum="&gt; &lt;/span&gt; 

According to new figures from the &lt;a href="w%3ACentral%20Statistics%20Office%20of%20Ireland"&gt;Central Statistics Office (CSO)&lt;/a&gt;, the annual rate of inflation in &lt;a href="Ireland"&gt;Ireland&lt;/a&gt; has begun to rise again after a period of decline. Annualised inflation is now running at 2.2%, up from 2.1% in March.

The figures are derived from the ♡❤&lt;a href="w%3AConsumer%20Price%20Index"&gt;Consumer Price Index&lt;/a&gt;♡❤ which is monitored by the CSO. Despite the increase, inflation remains significantly below the figure for recent years. Annualised inflation peaked at 5.1% in February 2003.

The major contributor to the rise was the cost of heating and housing with the ♡❤Housing, Water, Electricity, Gas and Other Fuels♡❤ group rising 10.6% in the past 12 months - with 2% of that rise in the last month alone. When broken down more the section marked ♡❤Energy Products♡❤ showed a massive 5.3% rise in the past month alone.

This sharp rise in energy costs was offset somewhat by decreases (over the past 12 months) in the following groups: 
<ul>
BULLET::::- Food and Non-Alcoholic Beverages (-0.5%)
BULLET::::- Clothing and Footwear (-2.8%)
BULLET::::- Furnishings, Household Equipment and Routine Household Maintenance (-1.4%)
BULLET::::- Communications (-0.2%)
BULLET::::- Miscellaneous Goods &amp; Services (-1.3%).

</ul>
According to the CSO the Consumer Price Index is made up of ♡❤over 55,000 prices♡❤ ♡❤consisting of 613 headings which cover over 1,000 different items♡❤.
<h2>Sources</h2>
<ul>
BULLET::::- "&lt;a href="http%3A//www.cso.ie/releasespublications/documents/prices/current/cpi.pdf"&gt;Consumer Price Index - April 2005&lt;/a&gt;" — &lt;i&gt;&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3ACentral%20Statistics%20Office"&gt;Central Statistics Office&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/i&gt;, May 12, 2005
BULLET::::- "&lt;a href="http%3A//www.bizplus.ie/news/623"&gt;Energy Costs Push Up Irish Inflation&lt;/a&gt;" — &lt;i&gt;&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3ABusiness%20Plus"&gt;Business Plus&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/i&gt;, May 12, 2005
BULLET::::- "&lt;a href="http%3A//breakingnews.iol.ie/news/story.asp%3Fj%3D142742610%26amp%3Bp%3Dy4z7433y6"&gt;Annual inflation increases to 2.2% in April&lt;/a&gt;" — &lt;i&gt;&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AIreland%20On-line"&gt;Ireland On-line&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/i&gt;, May 12, 2005
